AVIAN INFLUENZA - EURASIA (38): CYPRUS (NORTH), IRAQ
****************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Tue, 31 Jan 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters alertnews, 30 Jan 2006 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L30656495.htm>

Turkish Cypriot authorities said on Monday [30 Jan 2006] they were
worried an outbreak of avian flu among poultry could hit badly needed
tourism revenues and said they were stepping up efforts to prevent
the virus spreading.
The European Commission confirmed on Sunday the presence of the
deadly H5N1 strain of avian flu in a sample taken from poultry in
northern Cyprus.
Turkey, just to the north of Cyprus, has reported 21 human cases of
H5N1 since the start of 2006, including 4 deaths. Turkey has culled
about 1.5 million poultry to stem the disease.
"We are worried. It (bird flu) could have an effect, not just on the
north, but on the whole of the island," the head of Turkish Cypriot
hoteliers, Turan Beydagli, told Reuters.
Cyprus is divided into a prosperous, internationally recognised Greek
Cypriot south and a smaller, poorer Turkish Cypriot north which is
recognised only by Turkey. Despite continued international trade
restrictions, the north's economy has grown strongly in the past few
years, propelled mainly by tourism, construction and real estate.
Official figures show gross domestic product (GDP) in the
self-declared Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus (TRNC) leapt 31
percent in 2004 to 7350 USD per head -- still small compared to the
Greek Cypriots' 21 000 USD but a big jump from a low base.
Economy and Tourism Minister Dervis Deniz said it was too early to
say if the bird flu would harm economic growth.
"So far we have not seen an effect... on the economy as a whole. It
is only the 4 or 5 big commercial chicken farms that are losing out,
and that is purely because Turkish Cypriots are not buying chicken or
eggs as much as before," he said. "North Cyprus does not export
chicken, so a newly imposed ban on imports of poultry into the EU
from north Cyprus will not have an impact."
Health Minister Esref Vaiz said the situation in the enclave was
under control and that a surveillance zone around the infected
village of Incirli had been widened to 10 km (6 miles) from 3 km.
Authorities have already culled poultry in the infected area.
"We are checking all the surrounding villages to make sure all
domestic birds are confined so they cannot come into contact with
wildfowl," he said.
The Greek Cypriot government has said it has no plans to close any
crossing points to the north.
Nevruz Kavazlar, a housewife living in the infected North Cypriot
village, said: "There is no panic. We are sad that it turned up here,
but we are glad that it was discovered. But one thing has changed. We
used to be woken up by the neighbours' cockerel, but now we oversleep."
[Byline: Simon Bahceli]
