<promed@promedmail.org>
[An interactive map, reflecting the AI situation in Turkey and its
neighbours -- updated 31 Jan 2006 -- is available at
<http://disasters.jrc.it/AvianFlu/Turkey/>.
H5N1 has, so far, been confirmed in the following Near-Eastern
countries: Turkey, Cyprus (north), Iraq, Saudi Arabia and Kuwait. In
the latter 2, the virus was identified in captive birds.
2 other avian diseases, clinically very similar to H5N1, are endemic
in the region: Newcastle disease and avian influenza caused by the
LPAI serotype H9N2. Differential diagnosis of the 3 disease entities
can be achieved only by laboratory investigations.- Mod.AS]
[When dealing with zoonotic diseases with simultaneous outbreaks in
humans and animals, there are frequently reports that ProMED-mail
posts that contain information on both the human and animal
outbreaks. While we at ProMED-mail usually try to 'clearly' separate
the outbreaks into human health threads and animal health threads,
sometimes that line of distinction is difficult to make. In the
above article on the situation in Iraq [2], the information on the
human cases has already been covered in postings on the human health
thread of the avian influenza outbreak. The rationale for placing
this article in the animal health thread is the focus and discussion
on the observation that human cases have been confirmed in areas
where animal cases have not been confirmed, albeit are strongly
suspected (animal cases). To date, the overwhelming epidemiologic
evidence (and viral genetic evidence) has been that the human cases
of avian influenza have been associated with close contact with
diseased avians. Hence, the confirmation of human cases in Iraq,
combined with anecdotal evidence of avian die offs in the surrounding
area begs the issue that there are avian outbreaks in the area, and
there remains the need for improved surveillance in the animal health
sector. - Mod.MPP]
